  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 10.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - Was; rather, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "is. As a bear",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "is.",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "cmt_word",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": " As a bear",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "...as ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "a lion",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". The comparison of the enemy to a lion is not uncommon; see ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "e.g.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Jeremiah 4:7",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Jeremiah 5:6",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (see note); 49:19; 1:44; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 10:9",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 17:12",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Job 10:16",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". The bear is only once mentioned in such a context (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Hosea 13:8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). The two latter passages may possibly have been in the mind of the writer, as Jehovah is in both the subject of the comparison. Lamentations 3:10",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Not merely, however, has God cut off every way of escape for him who here utters the complaint, but He pursues him in every possible way, that He may utterly destroy him. On the figure of a bear lying in wait, cf. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Hosea 13:8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Amos 5:19",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". It is more usual to find enemies compared to lions in ambush; cf. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 10:19",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 17:12",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". The last-named passage seems to have been present to the writer's mind. The prophets frequently compare enemies to lions, e.g., ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Jeremiah 5:6",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Jeremiah 4:7",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Jeremiah 49:19",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Jeremiah 50:44",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". - In ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Lamentations 3:11",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " the figure of the lion is discontinued; for cowreer דּרכי cannot be said of a beast. The verb here is not to be derived from סרר, to be refractory, but is the Pilel of סוּר, to go aside, deviate, make to draw back. To \"make ways turn aside\" may signify to make a person lose the right road, but not to drag back from the road (Thenius); it rather means to mislead, or even facere ut deficiant viae, to take away the road, so that one cannot escape. פּשּׁח is ἅπ. λεγ. in Hebrew; in Aramean it means to cut or tear in pieces: cf. [the Targum on] ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Samuel 15:33",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", \"Samuel  פּשּׁח Agag,\" hewed him in pieces; and on ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 7:3",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", where the word is used for the Heb. פּרק, to tear in pieces (of a lion); here it signifies to tear away (limbs from the body, boughs from trees). This meaning is required by the context; for the following expression, שׂמני שׁומם, does not lead us to think of tearing in pieces, lacerating, but discerpere, plucking or pulling to pieces. For שׁומם, see on ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Lamentations 1:13",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Lamentations 1:16",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  }
